## Development Workflow

### Branch Strategy

- `main`: represents the desired state of all environments.
- Feature branches: `infra/short-description` (e.g., `infra/add-redis-cluster`).
- No direct commits to `main` — all changes via pull request.

### Pull Request Checklist

Before merging, every infrastructure PR must:

- [ ] Pass all linting and static analysis checks.
- [ ] Pass all unit tests.
- [ ] Include a `plan`/`diff` output in the PR description or as a CI comment.
- [ ] Reference the ticket/issue being addressed.
- [ ] Have at least one peer review from a team member with infrastructure experience.
- [ ] Update or add module `README.md` if inputs/outputs changed.
- [ ] Add or update an ADR if a significant architectural decision was made.
- [ ] Confirm no secrets or sensitive values are present in the code or plan output.

### Local Development

- Use `.tool-versions` (asdf) or a `Makefile` to pin tool versions — all team members use the same versions.
- `dev` environment is the only environment developers can `apply` directly from a local machine, with explicit approval.
- Always run `plan`/`diff` before `apply` and review the output — never apply blindly.
- Use workspaces or separate state keys to avoid colliding with team members' local development.

### Makefile Targets (recommended)

```makefile
make lint          # Run all linters and static analysis
make test          # Run unit tests
make plan ENV=dev  # Generate and display plan for the specified environment
make apply ENV=dev # Apply changes to the specified environment (requires confirmation)
make destroy ENV=dev # Destroy the specified environment (requires double confirmation)
```
